post_text:
The Ocosta School District has been awarded $20,000 from the Grays Harbor Community Foundation for the elementary music program. Music teacher, JR Lakey, started at Ocosta in the fall of 2019 and had very few materials to work with. Mr. Lakey is also the executive director of The Garage: Music and Arts Center in Aberdeen.
The district is excited that they have someone with such a vast background in the community leading the music program.
This grant will give Mr. Lakey the opportunity to buy the instruments and supplies to start a music program that can grow into a comprehensive music program district-wide. A bulk of the money will be to used to buy Orff instruments, which include xylophones, glockenspiels, and percussion instruments. District Superintendent, Heather Sweet, stated that there are so many possibilities for our students to learn music using Orff instruments.
The district greatly appreciates the support for the arts from GHCF.

shared_text:
Ocosta School PTO
August 28 at 12:02 AM ·

If you're looking at the proposed class schedules and wondering what in the world "synchronous" and "asynchronous" mean, you're not alone. I suspect we'll be seeing these words a lot for the next little bit, so let's clear it up. Synchronous refers to online classes learning together at the same time (this will take place via Google Meet). Asynchronous is independent self directed learning at your child's own pace (this will take place via apps on your chromebooks).

post_text:
Did you know that all Ocosta students are eligible for pandemic EBT cards?
This is supplemental funding for groceries from the state.

If you already qualify for EBT benefits you do not need to do anything, the additional funds will be added to your card automatically.

If you don't already receive benefits, here is a handy "how to" developed by the Aberdeen School District. It take about 15 minutes to apply. Thank you Aberdeen for the helpful document.

Every qualifying student receives a one time benefit of just under $400.

https://www.asd5.org/cms/lib/WA01001311/Centricity/Shared/NEWS%20RELEASES%20AND%20PUBLICITY/2020%20COMMUNICATIONS/CORONAVIRUS/Step%20by%20Step%20Instructions%20on%20Applying%20for%20Pandemic.pdf

Did you know that Washington State has new rules regarding immunization?
Students will no longer have a 30 day grace period after enrolling in school to complete their immunizations. In order for students to begin school, they must have proof that they have up-to-date immunizations. Pleas go to the link from Washington State Department of Health for more information.

https://www.doh.wa.gov/YouandYourFamily/Immunization/SchoolandChildCare/RuleChanges

Have kiddos at home? Do they have all sorts of questions about the coronavirus? ME TOO!

On Friday I’ll be hosting a KIDS town hall to help answer those questions! Join me, my daughter Tess, and pediatrician Dr. Katherine Herz for a LIVE Facebook event as we learn more about the coronavirus.

If your kiddo has a question – leave it below and we’ll get to as many as we can!

Ina works in the kitchen at the high school. During the quarantine she is preparing lunches and then goes out in the community to deliver meals and materials to our students!

In her free time she spends time with her daughter.

Thank you Ina!

In her down time she is enjoying spending time with her three children and her newest addition Obi, the puppy!

Thank you Lesley!

Today’s Senior Spotlight is Margaret Bartley. While in quarantine she is watching Netflix and taking care of Kelowna. She is missing being able to visit her family freely, and and not having to worry about doing simple tasks like, pumping gas, or going to the grocery store. Her plans after graduation are to continue her education at Grays Harbor College in their bachelors program to become an elementary teacher!

post_text: Pizza kit delivered to your door tomorrow!
shared_text:
Aloha Alabama BBQ
April 2 at 11:32 AM ·

Tomorrow (FRIDAY) special is the #ptopizzaparty. This $20 deal benefits the Ocosta PTO and includes 2 balls of dough, pizza sauce, cheese, pepperoni, and instructions on how to make 2 ~12” pizzas.
This is a super fun activity to keep the kids busy and engaged - it takes around 30-40 minutes ( including cook time) to get dinner on the table.

Pizzas can be picked up at Aloha Alabama 3-6pm on Friday or delivered to your address in Westport/Grayland (before Pomegranate).

You can order today (Thursday)for tomorrow here: http://ocostapto.square.site/

We are always looking for fun ways to keep our Westport and Wildcat family connected during this pandemic - if you have ideas please pm us!

shared_text:
Ocosta Counseling Program is celebrating Family Day.
March 19 at 6:04 PM ·

Good Evening Wildcat Families, check out this fun activity to go with Ms.Sweet's story time!

Lets talk about healthy "Cope Cakes". The kids hear it all the time from me. We have to practice healthy coping skills when we are calm and collected so when our "lizard brains" switch on, we know what to do. Now is a great time to practice those skills. You have to try a skill at least 3 times before you say "it didnt work".

Enjoy story time with Ms. Sweet and I cant wait to see all the home-made Cope Cakes!

post_text:
Please remember to complete the census! The official census day is on Wednesday, April 1. Everyone living in the borders on this day, should complete the census. There is not a citizenship question and all information is only held with the census and cannot be shared with other government agencies.

Go to census.gov and click the "respond now' button. You can resond even without a "census id" number, just click the words "If you do not have a Census ID, click here"

Did you know the census brings on avereage $1000 per person to a community with roads and other government grants and services.

https://2020census.gov/

post_text: We would normally send fliers home for these, but since we are not in school...this is the best we can do! Please reply with orders and we will collect payment at pickup. Thank you for always supporting the Ocosta Cheer team!
shared_text:
OHS Cheerleaders
March 24 at 8:17 AM ·

The cheerleaders are selling hanging baskets (12" for $30) and pots (14" for $20) from Degoede Bulb Farm in Mossyrock again this year. Flowers will be delivered to the school on May 9th and we are planning on being available for pickup between 10:00 - 12:00. If you got them last year, you know how amazing they are! Unfortunately, we are not able to send home flyers through school or have cheerleaders out selling this year. If you would like to order, please comment on this post, or contact Lesley Hatton (email is cranbogmama@gmail and phone is 360-580-2218). We appreciate everyone's support during such a crazy time in our lives! The funds from this fundraiser go towards sending the team to camp and uniforms for next year!! Jennifer Taylor Julie Soderlund Rissy Ness

shared_text:
Ocosta Counseling Program
March 21 at 11:36 AM ·

Family Activity to accompany Ms. Sweet’s Story

I picked a basic taco recipe, after thinking way too long about how cooking is a part of a families unique identity. How tacos are cooked in my house, probably are not the way they are cooked in yours. Take some time tonight and tell your kids what your families’ recipes are. Why are some foods saved for special occasions? Tell the stories of how you learned to cook. The mistakes you made along the way. Cooking #together is a great way to strengthen your families’ unique identity.

-Mrs.Todd
Share those taco recipes, picutures here...

#WeAreOcosta #SouthBeachStrong #together

We have put hand sanitizing stations in both of the kitchens as students enter to get their trays/food. We will be adding these same stations to the elementary, jr/senior high offices and the district office.

Starting next Monday, we are adding extra custodial support each night for at least the next two weeks to help sanitize surfaces in both buildings.

Earlier this week, we bought out the last of the hand sanitizer at Staples.

These are only precautionary steps to keep everyone safe and healthy!

This week is Classified Employee Appreciation Week!! This is an important recognition for the contributions and professional support they provide each day! “The Guiding Good Choices workshop series is for people who are parenting children
aged 9 - 14. Adults come to learn how to strengthen family bonds, set clear family
guidelines on drugs, help children develop healthy behaviors, and increase children’s
involvement in the family.”

We are providing this workshop at the Elementary starting March 2nd, and will run each Monday and Thursday from 6-8pm. This is a wonderful opportunity for community members to get together and learn how to have the difficult conversations. Sign up at Ocosta jr/sr high school or the elementary. If you have any questions please contact Andrea Mirante the After School Programs Director at 360-268-9125 ext 2021

post_text: Smart911 is the new emergency alert system that will be used by Grays Harbor County Emergency Management.
shared_text:
Ocosta Junior/Senior High School
February 24 at 9:16 PM ·

Passing on Information for Emergency Alerts from the county.

Grays Harbor County Emergency Management has changed public alerting systems. Citizens whom have previously signed up for notifications from Grays Harbor County Emergency Management will need to sign up for the new system in order to receive alerts via email, voice call and/ or text.

The new system is called Rave Alert/ Smart911. Benefits of this particular program includes targeted location-based alerts and important National Weather Service notifications to residents. Critical weather-related information, such as high winds, high surf advisories, flooding or tsunami warnings would be transmitted to citizens registered with Rave Alert/ Smart911.

The link to register for Rave Alert/ Smart911 is:

https://www.smart911.com/smart911/ref/reg.action?pa=graysharbor

Smart911
This service helps 9-1-1 protect your family by providing more information to first responders. You should sign up too, it is free!
